!! What is Algebraic Topology?
!!! Invariants Help Us Distinguish Spaces
    A classic technique for showing that two things are different is to demonstrate a property of
    one that doesn't hold for another.  For instance, this trick allows us to show that a circle
    and a real line are not homemorphic: one is compact, and the other isn't!  To show that five
    circles are not homeomorphic to ten circles, we can't invoke compactness, but we can count
    connected components.  However, other distinctions require subtler tools to see.  No elementary
    topological property distinguishes a one-holed torus from a two-holed torus, for example.
    Instead of associating a truth-value or number with each space, it turns out in this case to be
    more fruitful to associate a %group%.  *Algebraic topology* is the study of such
    algebraically flavored topological invariants.

