!!! Homotopy Equivalence
    We will investigate two invariants: the *fundamental group* and *singular homology*.  Both are
    preserved under not only homeomorphism but also %homotopy equivalence%.  It is easier for
    spaces to be homotopy equivalent than to be homeomorphic: the latter implies the former.  So
    the invariant technique cannot always distinguish nonhomeomorphic spaces.  The technique can't
    distinguish spaces that are too similar to each other, but when it %does% distinguish spaces,
    we know that they are %very% dissimilar.  Moreover, the invariants we will study are not even
    sufficient to reconstruct spaces up to homotopy equivalence.  This means two things: that we
    might still confuse very dissimilar spaces, and also that the converse problem of showing that
    these tools cannot show that two spaces are %the same%.

