!! The Fundamental Group
!!! The Fundamental Set
    For a space $X$, consider the continuous maps $:X\from S^1$.  Recall that two such maps $f,g$
    are %homotopic% when there is some continuous interpolator $h:X\from [0,1]\times S^1$ such that
    $h_0=f$ and $h_1=g$.  This is clearly an equivalence relation.  The resulting equivalence
    classes we will call %loops% in $X$.  The set $F(X)$ of loops is X's %fundamental set%. 

    For instance, $F(S^1)$ is infinite, while $F(\RR)$ is finite of size $1$.  Since $F$ is clearly
    invariant under homeomorphism, this provides another proof that $S^1$ and $\RR$ are not
    homeomorphic.

    Likewise, $F(S^2)$ is finite of size $1$, while $F(S^1\times S^1)$ is infinite.  This shows
    that the sphere and torus are not homeomorphic.  

    However, $F(T^{\#1})$ and $F(T^{\#2})$ are both countably infinite.  We need a finer invariant 
    to distinguish them.

    Before we do so, let's think about the fundamental set.  First, it is a functor from Top to
    Set.  It acts on morphisms in the natural way: if $s:X\from Y$ is continuous,
    then $F(s)$ sends the loop $f:Y\from S^1$ to the loop $s\circ f:X\from S^1$.    

    Thus, injections map to injections, so $S^1$ is not a deformation retract of the disk $D^2$. 

    Visualize in terms of torus.  View as generalization of path connected components.
    While path-connectedness is preserved by continuous maps, simple-connectedness is not.

!! The Fundamental Group
    To obtain a more powerful invariant, we needn't look far.  The idea is to consider
    relationships between loops, thus imposing further structure on the Fundamental Set.  In fact,
    we will modify our definitions slightly to allow %composition% of loops, yielding the
    Fundamental Group.  We can consider loops as paths when we fix a basepoint $\star\in S^1$.
    Then, if $f,g:X\from S^1$ are loops with $f(\star)=g(\star)$, we can compose the loops into
    $(fg):X\from S^1$ using the homotopy class of maps $:S^1\wedge S^1\from S^1$.  
    
